Part I - (Used car dataset exploration)¶

by Ujunwa Dike¶

Introduction¶

The user car dataset is a large dataset gathered by a consulting firm across the market through their market survey

Dataset Dictionary¶

  • sales_id: the recorded sales id
  • name: the name of the car/ the car company name -year: the year of purchase -selling_price: the selling price of the car -km_driven: the distance driven by the car in kilometers -region: the region the car is used -state: the state the car is used -city: the city where the car is used -fuel: the type of fuel used by the car -seller_type: who sells the car -transmission: the transmission type of the car -owner: the type of ownership -mileage: the distance travelled per gasoline/fuel used -engine the engine size in cubic centimeter(cc) -max_power: the power/horsepower of the car -torque: the turning force capacity in Newton meter(Nm) -max_rpm: the highest revolution per minute(rpm) -seats : the number of seats in the car -sold: the state of car, sold or not

#defining a function that will take the value counts for all categorical variables owner

def val_cnts():
    val_cnt1 = car['owner'].value_counts() #value count for owner
    val_cnt2 = car['transmission'].value_counts() #value count for transmission
    val_cnt3 = car['seller_type'].value_counts() #value count for seller_type
    val_cnt4 = car['fuel'].value_counts()#value count for fuel
    val_cnt5 = car['region'].value_counts() #value count for region
    val_cnt6 = car['sold'].value_counts()#value count for  sold
    val_cnt7 = car['seats'].value_counts()#value count for seats
    
    print(val_cnt1)
    print(val_cnt2)
    print(val_cnt3)
    print(val_cnt4)
    print(val_cnt5)
    print(val_cnt6)
    print(val_cnt7)

Some Issues from programmatic assessment¶

  • The fuel column has abbreviations as LGP and CNG
  • Y and N are used in the sold column

  • The seat columns have values in integers datatypes

  • year, selling_price, km_driven,year, engine, max_rpm, and max_power columns have either float or object datatypes

  • The data set has NaN values

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset has 7907 records of cars and 19 columns showing the features, attributes, characteristics, sales status and mechanical properties of each car in the dataset

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

the main feature of interest in this dataset are year of purchase, selling price or car worth and whether the cars have been sold or not.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The key features that can support this investigation would be the non-mechanical properties of cars such as seats number, region, name, and mechanical features like mileage, engine, max_power, torque, max_rpm etc

#creating a function that will provide the limits
def limit_finder(df):
    Q1 = df.quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = df.quantile(0.75)
    inter_quautile_range = IQR = Q3-Q1
    lower_limit_boundary = llb = Q1 - (IQR*1.5)
    upper_limit_boundary = ulb = Q3 + (IQR*1.5)
    print('this is lower boundary :',llb)
    print('this is upper boundary :', ulb)
    print('this is mean :', df.mean())

Observation¶

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The sold column reveals that about 25% of the cars in the dataset has been sold while the remaining 75% are still unsold. Interestingly, the mean price for cars sold and those not sold are almost equal at $676.60bn and $642.6bn respectively

The total worth of all cars at their purchase are$5.137bn. The minimum and maximum price for cars in the dataset are $29.999k and $10bn respectively.

Finally, the dataset reveals that most of the purchase cars where purchased between 2010 and 2020.

No transformation was done on the dataset in relation to the key features. Although, some selling price values were above the upper limits, these values were significantly high in number and could affect the integrity of the data if deleted.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

The cleaning of the data set was done before the distribution of the variables were plotted.

Changing of the abbreviated data such as LPG to liquified petroleum gas in the fuel column, and Y to yes in the sold column. This was done in order to make the data easier to read.

Null values were also removed as these values would make the data unfit for analysis

Values of 0 were removed as it was not possible for a car to have some technical properties as 0; for instance, the presence of 0 in the mileage column.

The seat column had data values in digits to represent the number of seats, however these values are categorical in nature hence it was best to change them to stringed and spelt terms.

Other major quality issues were cleaned, for instance, the changing of columns' datatypes, this was in order to make it easy to assess and analyze the data/column

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

The dataset reveals that over time, the features of cars purchased increased, this include engine sizes, car power, mileage and selling price. However, the kilometer driven by car owners over the years reduced.

The selling price of cars also increased as the engine size increases

The dealer seller type of cars showed to be more expensive despite being the drastically lower in number than the individually sold cars. The cheapest are the individual-seller type of cars going as low as 26K in dollars.

The Test_drive_cars also showed to be most expensive reaching about $6m although these cars are the least available in the dataset. The cheapest are the fourth-and-above owner type of cars

The five-seater type of cars also showed to be most expensive ranging up to 7million in dollars. The least expensive are the fourteen-seater type of cars. Later, the combination of seater-type and owner-type that is most expensive or cheapest will be determined

The most expensive cars in relation to fuel type are the diesel-powered type of cars while following immediately in second place are the petrol-powered cars.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

There’s a strong correlation between engine size and cars’ horsepower. The cars with the highest engine sizes have the highest power. In other words, high engine sizes produce high horsepower

There’s a negative correlation between the car power and the fuel per distance consumed by a car. This explains that cars of lower horsepower would use high amount fuel per distance during movement, this in turn would increase demand of fuel on the car user.

The dataset also revealed that most of the cars are first-owner type of cars.

Finally, the dataset reveal that cars already not sold out had greater distribution in most categorical variable than those sold out, in order words, they appeared appeared in greater amount than the cars sold out. This could explain why first_owner cars are greatest in number.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

During the multivariate the total number of cars not sold out is greater than those sold out in all variables and categories.

The data also reveal that four-seater types of cars were purchase over a long time and those of them that have been sold out by their owners were only purchased within a short period of time.

The data also reveals that although dealer seller-type cars are more expensive, the cars that have been sold are more expensive than the ones not sold.

Majority of the cars have low prices below 4million have equivalently low engine sizes and most of them are five-seater cars. The cars with the highest engines are not highly priced and they are majorly seven and eight-seater vehicles. However, there’s no significant difference between those sold out and those not sold out in relation to the price, engine size and seat numbers.

The four-seater vehicles are least expensive at the western region and most of them have not been sold. A prospect looking to buy four-seater car should look west.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

Four-seater unsold vehicles for family use are cheapest in the West.

Expensive cars are least available in the dataset and BMW vehicles are the most expensive and not sold out yet.

None of the test_drive_cars (which are the most expensive type of cars in relation to car ownership) have been sold. Interestingly these cars have been driven a few kilometers below 25Km. These test-driven cars have engine sizes between 2000cc and 1500cc which is above the mean engine size.

Conclusions¶

The used_car dataset contain a lot of explorable datapoints. The steps taken during the exploration were aimed at comparing the distribution of features of interest and other(supplementary) features. First, the distribution of the different data types; continuous, discrete and categorical data. Then, the bivariate exploration examined the nature of correlation between the mechanical features of the car as well as the distribution of these features over the categorical data. Finally at the multivariate exploration stage, the insights gotten from the bivariate exploration were used to further explore the additon of a third variable(both categorical and discrete).

The dataset revealed some major findings.

  1. 25% of the cars in the dataset has been sold while the remaining 75% are still unsold. Interestingly, the mean price for both types of cars are almost equivalent at $676.60bn and $642.6bn respectively
  2. The total worth of all cars at their purchase are$5.137bn.
  3. The minimum and maximum price for cars in the dataset are $29.999k and $10bn respectively.
  4. Purchase of cars were majorly done between 2010 and 2020.
  5. The selling price of cars also increased as the engine size increases
  6. Over the course of time, the features of cars purchased increased, this included engine sizes, car power, mileage and selling price
  7. The Test_drive_cars also showed to be most expensive reaching up to $6m
  8. There’s a negative correlation between the car power and the fuel per distance consumed by a car. This explains that cars of lower horsepower would use high amount fuel per distance during movement, this in turn would increase demand of fuel on the car user.
  9. Most cars are first-owner type cars.
  10. Four-seater unsold vehicles ( probable for family use) were cheapest in the West.
  11. Majority of the cars have low prices below 4million have equivalently low engine sizes and most of them are five-seater cars.
  12. None of the test_drive_cars (which are the most expensive type of cars in relation to car ownership) have been sold out. This makes sense as they were still test driven.
